rop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001106047"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="574" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-516024?width=860&amp;height=574" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">根据 Data Bridge Market Research 的数据，未来六年，全球人工智能基础设施市场的支出预计将以 44% 的复合年增长率增长。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：安德烈·鲁达科夫/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001106047"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/angus-loten" itemprop="url" rel="author">安格斯·洛滕</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日上午 9:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-ready-data-centers-are-poised-for-fast-growth-fadae952"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>企业对人工智能永无止境的需求正在推动数据中心市场的快速崛起，该市场旨在处理计算密集型人工智能应用程序。</p><p>分析师表示，随着经验丰富的企业云供应商竞相用先进芯片和其他升级改造现有数据中心，以满足人工智能软件的需求，一些新贵建筑商看到了从头开始开发新设施的机会。</p><p>数据中心是类似仓库的建筑，配备了多个服务器机架、路由器和其他用于存储和处理数据的信息技术硬件。 IT 服务和咨询公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UIS" class="">Unisys</a>云、应用程序和基础设施解决方案高级副总裁兼总经理 Manju Naglapur 表示，传统数据中心通常配备使用标准通用芯片运行工作负载的服务器<span class="company-name-type">。</span></p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>他说，一个专门建造的人工智能数据中心配备了利用人工智能芯片的服务器， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-next-challengers-joining-nvidia-in-the-ai-chip-revolution-e0055485?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">例如英伟达的图形处理单元</a>，当人工智能应用程序<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-ai-boom-is-here-the-cloud-may-not-be-ready-1a51724d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">筛选大量数据</a>时，这些服务器可以同时运行多个计算。他说，他们还提供光网络和更高效的存储来支持大规模的人工智能模型。</p><p> Naglapur 表示：“这需要大量资金和时间投资来检修现有中心或创建这些新的专用数据中心。”</p><p>全球人工智能基础设施市场（包括数据中心、网络和其他支持人工智能应用的硬件）的支出预计到 2029 年将达到 4225.5 亿美元，未来六年复合年增长率为 44%据研究公司 Data Bridge Market Research 称。</p><p>总部位于新泽西州罗斯兰的数据中心初创公司 CoreWeave 周四表示，在对冲基金 Magnetar Capital 和私募股权公司 Blackstone 的支持下，该公司已获得 23 亿美元的债务融资，该融资将用于加速人工智能的建设准备好数据中心。在最新一轮融资之前，该公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/generative-ai-cloud-startup-coreweave-raises-221-million-megaround-f817b027?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在 4 月份进行了 2.21 亿美元的 B 轮融资</a>，并在 5 月份进行了 2 亿美元的 B 轮延期融资。</p><p> CoreWeave 首席技术官布莱恩·文图罗 (Brian Venturo) 表示，CoreWeave 于六年前推出，目前拥有七个在线人工智能数据中心，预计到今年年底这一数字将增加一倍。 Venturo 表示，其最新的数据中心位于德克萨斯州普莱诺，占地 45 万平方英尺，价值约 16 亿美元，已于本周开始商业运营。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="304" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828714?width=700&amp;height=304" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> CoreWeave 位于德克萨斯州普莱诺的人工智能就绪数据中心已于本周上线。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：CoreWeave</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “大约在去年的这个时候，我们开始了解即将发生的事情，”Venturo 说道，他引用了 2022 年 8 月发布的 Stability AI 的 Stable Diffusion（一款人工智能驱动的图像生成器）。他说，三个月后，OpenAI 的在线聊天机器人 ChatGPT 的公开发布让人工智能市场进入了高速发展阶段。 “那时我们就想‘这一切都成真了’，”文图罗说。</p><p>除其他差异外，人工智能数据中心比传统数据中心拥有更多运行高性能芯片的服务器。因此，分析师表示，人工智能数据中心全栈服务器的平均功耗可以达到每个机架 50 千瓦或更多，而传统数据中心每个机架的平均功耗约为 7 千瓦。</p><p>这意味着人工智能数据中心需要增加基础设施来提供更多的电力。由于额外的用电量会产生更多的热量，人工智能数据中心还需要替代的冷却方法，例如液体冷却系统，以防止设备过热。数据中心的租赁费率通常基于功耗。</p><p>其他建设人工智能数据中心的公司包括 Turner Construction、Holder Construction 和 DPR Construction 等公司，以及 DataBank 等数据中心运营商。</p><p>总部位于达拉斯的 DataBank 表示，今年 4 月，位于亚特兰大的一座 200,000 平方英尺的数据中心破土动工，该数据中心专为高性能计算（包括生成式人工智能）而设计。目前，该公司在 27 个市场运营着超过 65 个设施。数据银行首席执行官</p>Raul Martinek 表示，除了对传统信息技术工作负载的强劲需求之外，人工智能部署的步伐可能会导致未来 12 至 24 个月内数据中心容量短缺。<p></p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Facebook</a>母公司 Meta Platforms 去年年底暂停了在德克萨斯州坦普尔建设耗资 8 亿美元的人工智能数据中心的建设计划，因为它考虑重新设计这座约 90 万平方英尺的设施。 Meta 发言人表示，爱达荷州和阿拉巴马州的两个类似项目也被搁置，所有三个设施的施工预计将在今年年底前恢复。</p><p>随着企业在未来一年以更快的速度部署人工智能工具，传统数据中心可能无法跟上。国际数据公司 (International Data Corp.) 研究云到边缘数据中心趋势的研究总监 Sean Graham 估计，数据中心总容量的约 20% 用于人工智能。</p><p>根据商业房地产服务公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CBRE?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">CBRE Group</a>的估计，在拥有超过 275 个设施的数据中心市场领导者北弗吉尼亚州，今年可供租赁的电量从一年前的 46.6 兆瓦减少至 38.4 兆瓦。分析师表示，在几天内，单个人工智能模型可能会消耗数万千瓦时的电力。</p><p> Naveen Chhabra 表示，当企业从测试人工智能应用程序转向全面部署时，已经以接近峰值负载运行的现有数据中心将难以应对，</p> IT 研究公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/FORR" class="">Forrester Research</a>首席分析师<span class="company-name-type">。</span><p></p><p> “这就像说你需要一条八车道的道路，而不是一条两车道的道路来驱动你的人工智能应用程序，”查布拉说。</p><p>写信给安格斯·洛滕 (Angus Loten)： <a href="mailto:Angus.Loten@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Angus.Loten@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 13:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-ready-data-centers-are-poished-for-fast-growth-fadae952</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-ready-data-centers-are-poished-for-fast-growth-fadae952<author><![CDATA[Angus Loten]]></author><category>人工智能技术</category><category>计算机服务</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>数据中心/托管服务</category><category>数据服务</category><category>技术</category><category>企业融资</category><category>融资协议</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>系列/轮融资</category><category>人工智能/机器学习</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>企业融资</category><category>融资协议</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>系列</category><category>轮融资</category><category>人工智能</category><category>机器学习</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>计算机服务</category><category>商业</category><category>消费服务</category><category>数据中心</category><category>托管服务</category><category>数据服务</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Real Reason You’re Having a Hard Time Getting Things Done at the Office]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在家工作改变了我们的大脑。我们需要更多的办公时间来解决这些问题。 <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828457/?width=2000&amp;size=1.5" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>照片插图：Sam Kelly/《华尔街日报》，iStock (11)<span>照片插图：Sam Kelly/《华尔街日报》，iStock (11)</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105097"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105097"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ray-a-smith" itemprop="url" rel="author">雷·A·史密斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-real-reason-youre-having-a-hard-time-getting-things-done-at-the-office-5dc138f1"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>如果你还没有恢复办公室的最佳状态，可能会有一个科学的解释。混合工作安排会扰乱我们的大脑。</p><p>沮丧的老板们在审视<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-return-to-office-rate-rises-above-50-for-first-time-since-pandemic-began-11675285071?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">半空的办公室环境</a>后表示，2020 年之前在办公室全职工作的人不能像以前那样出现，这是没有道理的。但神经学家和行为科学家表示，对彼此有效合作的集体失忆症对他们来说是完全合理的。</p><p>一些员工已经失去了在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-open-office-is-out-seated-privacy-is-in-as-cubicles-make-a-comeback-11663189508?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">开放式办公室环境</a>中完成工作所需的肌肉记忆，就像松弛的二头肌一样，这种肌肉必须通过锻炼才能增强，教授兼神经病学系主任托马斯·卡迈克尔 (S. Thomas Carmichael) 说。加州大学洛杉矶分校大卫格芬医学院。</p><p>卡迈克尔说，经过多年的远程工作，我们大脑的选择性注意力技能和排除干扰的能力被削弱。那些喜欢在家工作的人可能不喜欢他的补救措施之一：让自己更频繁地在办公室工作。</p><p> “大脑真的很擅长理解突发事件，所以如果我们只是说‘我在家的时候就完成这件事’，我们也学不会它，”他说。</p><h3>淹没在“假设”的海洋中</h3><p>组织心理学家凯瑟琳·斯沃迪 (Cathleen Swody) 表示，在了解在家工作的有效性之后，人们心里产生了一种隐隐约约的不快感。许多员工在社交办公空间中失去了不受干扰的自主权。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="479" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828332?width=639&amp;height=479" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">玛丽亚·巴比诺娃 (Maryia Babinova) 表示，即使是很小的办公室时间浪费也已成为一大烦恼。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：玛丽亚·巴比诺娃</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>早在 2021 年，纽约市的高级软件工程师玛丽亚·巴比诺娃 (Maryia Babinova) 曾尝试每周去办公室几天，但发现几乎不可能提高工作效率。</p><p> “我每天的前 30 到 45 分钟都用来和每个人打招呼，”她说。</p><p>巴比诺娃表示，即使是很小的办公室时间浪费也已成为一大烦恼。例如，当排队时，去办公室的咖啡机可能需要长达 15 分钟的时间。她说，在家里，咖啡因触手可及，让她能够专注于工作。</p><p>现在，只有当她的团队成员从另一个城市来访时，巴比诺娃才会亲自出现。在办公室，她处理的任务不需要太多的精神负担，因此她可以完成它们。</p><p>伦敦经济学院助理教授劳拉·M·乔治 (Laura M. Giurge) 教授工作时间科学课程，她表示，不断将 2023 年的办公室现实与其他远程工作设置进行比较可能会加剧员工的重新调整困境。</p><p>当人们开始思考如果环境不同的话生活会是什么样子时，他们很快就会陷入“假设”的海洋，这是一种被称为反事实思维的心理学概念。</p><p> “现在，当我们去办公室时，我们会看到家庭办公室的反事实情况，”朱尔格说。 “我们知道事情会好得多……我们可以完成更多的工作。”</p><p>我们很难忘记<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-workers-really-spend-their-days-d06c8f5f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">中午带着狗去散步</a>是多么美好，或者下午 4 点退出去开始吃晚饭并稍后重新登录是多么有帮助。心理学家表示，思考如何更好地利用时间会占用宝贵的脑力，分散我们对手头实际工作的注意力。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=88CDF171-D046-4FD4-A4BB-72130DCCB4C6&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fthe-real-reason-youre-having-a-hard-time-getting-things-done-at-the-office-5dc138f1&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">由于住房供应短缺，开发商正在将更多空置办公室改造成公寓。但并非所有建筑物都适合重复利用，尽管美国各地有超过 10 亿平方英尺的办公空间闲置 图片插图：Amber Bragdon<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><h3>令人不安的安静</h3><p>习惯与背景噪音一起工作需要时间。</p><p>现在，许多工作场所变得更加安静，因为它们不再那么拥挤，这意味着，在一段死寂的时期，可能会被突然的噪音打断，这些噪音感觉被放大了，一整天都让人们一次又一次感到不安。即使是在一天在家孤独工作和第二天在嘈杂的办公室之间切换也会产生类似的效果。</p><p>康奈尔大学组织行为学教授凡妮莎·博恩斯 (Vanessa Bohns) 表示：“我们必须重新习惯所有这些干扰，才能做好工作。”她指出，研究表明，需要 20 分钟才能适应背景噪音，但在恢复噪音之前保持五分钟的安静会迫使大脑重新开始处理过程。</p><p>现在，许多员工和一些老板将办公室视为协作的场所，但并不是埋头进行个人工作的唯一场所。</p><p>在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="company-name">微软</a>去年发布的一项大规模调查中，84% 的员工表示，与同事交流是他们面对面工作的主要动机。超过 70% 的人表示，如果他们知道直接团队成员或工作朋友会在那里，他们会更频繁地去办公室。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您是否发现在办公室完成工作比大流行之前更困难？为什么或者为什么不？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> “数据显示，我们不能只将办公室视为完成集中工作的地方，”微软未来工作部总经理科莱特·斯塔尔鲍默 (Colette Stallbaumer) 表示。</p><p> Lynn Dang 是达拉斯地区的一名软件开发人员，她利用三天的强制办公时间进行面对面的会议和不需要高度集中注意力的工作。</p><p>去年，当她回到办公室时，她发现自己无法像在家工作时那样专心阅读代码。大声的团队讨论以及在小隔间里无意中听到那些正在打电话或拨入视频会议的人的片面谈话，对她的感官造成了持续的攻击。</p><p> “这就像我必须在我的待办事项清单上找到一些能让我高效工作的事情，”她说。 “否则我将不得不继续加班或周末工作才能完成工作。”</p><p>写信给 Ray A. Smith： <a href="mailto:Ray.Smith@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Ray.Smith@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-real-reason-youre-having-a-hard-time-getting-things-done-at-the-office-5dc138f1</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-real-reason-youre-having-a-hard-time-getting-things-done-at-the-office-5dc138f1<author><![CDATA[Ray A. Smith]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>工作与生活的平衡</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>远程办公</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> S·托马斯·卡迈克尔</category><category>凯瑟琳·斯沃迪</category><category>劳拉·M·乔治</category><category>凡妮莎·博恩斯</category><category>科莱特·斯托鲍默</category><category>工作与生活的平衡</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>远程办公</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China’s Latest Problem: People Don’t Want to Go There]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>随着地缘政治紧张局势加剧，前往世界第二大经济体的游客减少，东西方鸿沟扩大<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100887"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827041?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">近日，上海机场人烟稀少，旅行社组织的境外旅游来华的人数大幅减少。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：劳尔·阿里亚诺/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100887"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/wenxin-fan" itemprop="url" rel="author">范文欣</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a83a"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>中国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-xi-jinping-reversed-his-zero-covid-policy-in-china-11672853171?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">取消Covid-19限制</a>并重新开放边境半年后，几乎没有国际游客前来——这是中国与西方脱钩的另一个迹象，可能会产生长期负面影响。</p><p>外国游客的缺席在北京和上海等主要城市尤其明显，上半年到访这些城市的外国人人数总计不到 2019 年新冠疫情大流行前可比数字的四分之一。</p><p>在全国范围内，第一季度，只有 52,000 人次通过旅行社组织的旅行到达中国大陆，这是有全国数据的最新时期，而 2019 年第一季度有 370 万人次。与往年一样，近一半的游客来自自治岛屿台湾以及中国香港和澳门，而不是美国或欧洲等更远的地方。</p><p> “来自欧洲、美洲、日本和韩国的游客数量都在大幅下降，”半官方的中国旅游协会理事肖千惠在五月份的一次讲话中表示。</p><p>专家表示，海外游客和商人的减少意味着外国人亲眼看到中国并与当地人互动的机会减少，而这是缓解地缘政治紧张局势的一个重要因素。</p><p>游客稀缺也可能导致对华投资减少。研究公司荣鼎集团 (Rhodium Group) 的马克·维茨克 (Mark Witzke) 对政府数据进行的分析显示，第一季度<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/xi-china-economy-capital-investment-3439d31a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">流入该国的外国直接投资降至</a>200 亿美元，而去年第一季度为 1000 亿美元。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827059?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2019 年，新冠疫情爆发之前，南京的一座陵墓挤满了游客。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：苏洋/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>外国投资和入境人数下降之际，中国经济停滞不前， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-property-market-enters-troubling-new-phase-1fe3143d" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">房地产市场低迷</a>，青年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-youth-unemployment-xi-jobs-522028c5" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">失业率</a>创历史新高，人们越来越担心中国可能<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/while-everyone-else-fights-inflation-chinas-deflation-fears-deepen-4045cabf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">陷入通货紧缩。</a>与今年前三个月相比，第二季度<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-barely-grows-as-recovery-fades-5652a92a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">中国经济几乎没有增长</a>。</p><p>抵达中国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-allows-chinese-airlines-to-increase-flights-to-12-a-week-814327a8" target="_blank" class="icon none">的航班数量不足</a>是造成抵达人数低的部分原因，航空公司尚未恢复到新冠疫情爆发前提供的服务水平。但中国和海外旅游专家表示，由于中国与西方关系恶化，外国游客也不愿前往，这让他们对访问更加谨慎。</p><p> 6月，美国政府发布旅行建议，警告美国人重新考虑前往中国大陆的旅行，因为所谓的“任意执行当地法律”，包括出境禁令和错误拘留的可能性。</p><p>波士顿商业顾问马特·凯利 (Matt Kelly) 表示，他对 15 年前骑自行车环游中国南方一座风景如画的山城桂林的旅行留下了美好的回忆。他又两次访问中国，但表示今天没有兴趣回去。</p><p> “我会回到我所熟悉的中国吗？是的！”他说。但现在，“中国似乎确实将自己描绘成非常反西方、反美国的人。这让我非常不安。”</p><p>位于宾夕法尼亚州的友好星球旅游公司（Friendly Planet Travel）是一家精品经营商，过去每年向中国派遣多达 1,500 名游客。其创始人兼总裁佩吉·戈德曼 (Peggy Goldman) 表示，自新冠疫情爆发以来，该公司还没有收到过任何要求。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="479" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828850?width=639&amp;height=479" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">马特·凯利，2008 年在中国桂林。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：马特·凯利</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>当她的团队研究人们在网上搜索的目的地时，“中国确实处于追踪的底部，”她说。 “围绕中国这个话题存在很多敌意。”</p><p>尽管高盛表示她相信中国最终会再次流行，但该公司尚未将其中国包裹重新上线。</p><p>总部位于奥斯汀的旅游科技公司 Mondee Holdings 的数据显示，2023 年上半年从北美到中国的休闲旅游约为 2019 年同期的 40%。 2019年，Mondee通过旅行社和其他中介机构销售了约50万个从北美飞往中国的航班，约占当年从北美飞往中国的所有航空旅行的五分之一。</p><p>哈里斯·布里肯律师事务所驻西雅图合伙人丹·哈里斯表示，尽管企业高管仍在询问前往中国的旅行，但许多人现在关注的是风险，而过去，他们想知道如何加快签证速度。为在中国的投资提供建议。</p><p> “公司非常非常关心他们的员工去中国。为什么他们不会呢？他提到了中国最近<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/foreign-firms-in-china-squeezed-by-u-s-disclosure-demands-beijings-security-clampdown-658ef8f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">对西方尽职调查公司和其他公司进行调查</a>的消息，其中包括政府对贝恩公司等全球咨询公司进行突击搜查。“除非迫不得已，否则人们不会去中国。”</p><p>哈里斯过去经常去中国北京工作，并在青岛停留购买啤酒和海鲜，他表示，他已告诉一些高管，他们的风险很低。但近年来，在公开批评中国政府后，他本人不再前往。</p><p>中国文化和旅游部没有回应置评请求。</p><p>中国官员最近与美国、欧洲和日本的商业协会举行了会议<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-rushes-to-shore-up-battered-private-economy-skepticism-abounds-80c1a23c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，向他们保证</a>中国仍然欢迎外国投资。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="441" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827025?width=700&amp;height=441" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2019年以来，张家界国家公园的游客量大幅下降。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：吴永兵/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>中国驻美国大使谢锋7月份在阿斯彭安全论坛上表示，两国游客应该互相访问。他建议举办旅游论坛并增加航班数量，并呼吁华盛顿调整其旅行建议。</p><p>外国游客的缺席不会像泰国或冰岛那样对中国造成伤害，因为这些国家的经济严重依赖游客。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-travelers-swarm-domestic-tourist-sites-a-positive-sign-for-economy-f45c4977?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">目前，中国游客在国内旅游上的支出比 2019 年更多</a>。</p><p>尽管如此，中国仍有许多企业依赖游客。缺乏它们意味着中国失去了向外国人展示更积极形象的机会。</p><p>中国中部的张家界国家公园是电影《阿凡达》中“浮山”的拍摄地，这里有令人惊叹的岩层，截至 5 月中旬，海外游客仅有 25,600 人次，而 2019 年前 5 个月的海外游客人数为 500,000 人次。</p><p>上海导游于雪（Snow Yu）过去带外国人参观的生意很红火，包括在 2017 年为金州勇士队和佐治亚理工学院黄夹克篮球队的高管担任导游。在疫情期间，边境基本关闭，他找了一份英语辅导的临时工作。</p><p>于已经回到了原来的工作岗位，主要带领当地的旅游团。但他们不需要他的英语能力，给的小费也较少。因此，他说他的收入比大流行前减少了近一半。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=5BD0F48A-0DA4-4CED-8A69-018103B38E36&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fchinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a83a&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">拜登总统周日在日本七国集团会议结束的新闻发布会上表示，他认为美中关系可能出现解冻。照片：苏珊·沃尔什/美联社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“世界需要互联，”他说，并补充说来自邻国的英语游客开始回来。</p><p>来自西方和东亚部分地区游客的下降已被俄罗斯游客数量的增加部分抵消，不过中国旅游专家表示，他们的消费有所减少。</p><p>今年6月，张家界国家公园邀请80多家国际旅行社进驻，其中大部分来自俄罗斯。当地官员承诺增加更多从中国北方邻国起飞的航班，或延长从中国其他城市起飞的现有航班。</p><p>旅游官员肖在讲话中呼吁中央政府提供更多支持。他强调，入境旅游可以“以类似于‘乒乓外交’的方式”帮助化解地缘政治紧张局势，他指的是20世纪70年代乒乓球运动员的交流，帮助中美关系解冻。</p><p>他引用了埃隆·马斯克母亲最近访问中国的例子，她在 Instagram 上发布了关于她的经历的积极信息。</p><p>另一个避开中国的群体是外籍人士，他们在前几年充当了中国社会与各自祖国之间的桥梁。许多人邀请家人和朋友来参观。</p><p> 37岁的投资顾问亚历山大·西拉科夫(Alexander Sirakov)去年8月从上海搬回祖国保加利亚。他说，他的外籍朋友圈子里的大多数人也都离开了，包括住在他大院里的 10 个外籍家庭中的 8 个。</p><p> “人们现在认为中国非常遥远，而且有些疏远，”他说。 “四年前正好相反，当时的中国非常开放、充满活力，是一个必去的地方。”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——齐丽艳对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给范文欣： <a href="mailto:wenxin.fan@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">wenxin.fan@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a​​83a</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a​​83a<author><![CDATA[Wenxin Fan]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>呼吸道疾病</category><category>国际关系</category><category>健康</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>新型冠状病毒</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>旅行</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>呼吸道疾病</category><category>国际关系</category><category>健康</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>政治</category><category>新型冠状病毒</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>旅行</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Meta’s Ray-Ban Smart Glasses Fail to Catch On]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>公司计划推出第二代产品，因为购买的设备每月使用率不到 10% <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105934"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="568" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826586?width=860&amp;height=568" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">雷朋 Stories 智能眼镜允许用户使用镜框拍照、听音乐等功能。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：大卫·保罗·莫里斯/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105934"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/salvador-rodriguez" itemprop="url" rel="author">萨尔瓦多·罗德里格斯</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/joanna-stern" itemprop="url" rel="author">乔安娜·斯特恩</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 3 日上午 12:02（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/metas-ray-ban-smart-glasses-fail-to-catch-on-31f6ba4e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Meta Platforms</a>近两年前推出的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rayban-stories-facebook-review-11631193687?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">雷朋智能眼镜</a>一直难以赢得用户的青睐，根据公司内部数据，其中许多人似乎很少使用这些设备。</p><p>据《华尔街日报》查阅的 2 月份公司文件显示，自 2021 年 9 月产品推出以来，购买的 Ray-Ban Stories 中只有不到 10% 被购买者积极使用。截至 2 月份， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Meta</a>总共售出了 30 万台可穿戴设备，但该公司的月活跃用户仅有约 27,000 名。</p><p>该设备是 Meta 硬件战略的重要组成部分，除其他功能外，它还允许用户通过眼镜框拍照和听音乐。文件显示，它的退货率为 13%。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=D340813E-FD24-4A69-98A6-4EDEFF32F1C7&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fmetas-ray-ban-smart-glasses-fail-to-catch-on-31f6ba4e&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">自从莉娜·汗 (Lina Khan) 成为联邦贸易委员会主席以来，她已经与 Meta、微软和亚马逊较量，这让她成为了避雷针。图片插图：沉星培<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>造成用户体验不佳的主要原因包括连接问题、某些硬件功能（包括电池寿命）问题、用户无法从设备导入媒体、产品音频问题以及智能眼镜语音命令问题，根据文件。</p><p>文件称：“我们还需要更好地了解用户停止使用眼镜的原因，如何确保我们鼓励新功能的采用，以及最终如何保持用户的参与度和留存率。”</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> Meta 发言人拒绝对该文件发表评论。<br><br>据知情人士透露，尽管最初的销量不佳，但 Meta 希望在秋季（赶上假日购物季）或明年春季发布第二代 Ray-Ban Stories 智能眼镜。</p><p>这款智能眼镜是与<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/ESLOY" class="">EssilorLuxottica</a>合作开发的<span class="company-name-type">，</span>该公司生产和销售多种类型的眼镜，包括雷朋 (Ray-Ban) 和奥克利 (Oakley) 等品牌。 EssilorLuxottica 发言人拒绝置评。</p><p> Ray-Ban Stories 是 Meta 现实实验室部门最重要的合作伙伴之一，据数据显示，该部门在 2023 年前六个月累计运营亏损近 80 亿美元，预计 2024 年运营亏损将大幅增加高管。</p><p>该公司发布了该设备的第一个版本，大约一个月后将其名称从 Facebook 更改为 Meta，这是首席执行官<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/mark-zuckerberg">马克·扎克伯格</a><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mark-zuckerberg-to-sketch-out-facebooks-metaverse-vision-11635413402?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">构建元宇宙愿景</a>的一部分，元宇宙是用户可以在其中相互交互的互联网版本。实时的虚拟空间。其他科技公司一直在努力生产智能眼镜，其中包括谷歌，该公司已停止生产谷歌眼镜产品。</p><p>与当前版本一样，新版本预计不会具有增强现实的功能，增强现实允许可穿戴设备将内容投影或叠加到人们在现实世界中看到的内容中。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=C88AF8C6-9381-4531-8397-8E3466D42127&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fmetas-ray-ban-smart-glasses-fail-to-catch-on-31f6ba4e&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> 《华尔街日报》的乔安娜·斯特恩 (Joanna Stern) 剖析了埃隆·马斯克 (Elon Musk) 和马克·扎克伯格 (Mark Zuckerberg) 之间的争吵实际上就像过去硅谷的争吵一样。图片插图：Kenny Wassus、Preston Jessee<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>但 Meta 高管将 Stories 设备视为增强现实眼镜的前身，希望在未来几年推出。<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AAPL" class="company-name">苹果</a></p>最近在 6 月份的一次活动中展示了其 Vision Pro AR 耳机。扎克伯格和其他公司领导人表示，Meta 在这一领域的工作对于成为下一个主要计算平台的主导者至关重要。<p></p><p>知情人士称，第二代 Ray-Ban Stories 将配备更长的电池寿命和更好的摄像头，并将应用于更多型号的 Ray-Ban 镜框。目前，雷朋 (Ray-Ban) 的三款型号均配备了智能眼镜技术。</p><p>第一代 Ray-Ban Stories 起价为 299 美元。目前，雷朋 (Ray-Ban) 网站上有两种版本的眼镜可享受 30% 的折扣。目前还无法确定第二代产品的定价方式。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>你买Meta的智能太阳镜了吗？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>该文件称，Meta 计划提高设备的质量以及用户发现其功能的方式。文件显示，这家社交媒体巨头设定的目标是将智能眼镜使用的应用程序在苹果 App Store 或谷歌 Play Store 上的评级维持在 4.0 或更高。</p><p>该应用程序名为 Facebook View，目前在 Apple App Store 上的评分为 4.5，在 Google Play Store 上的评分为 4.4。</p><p> Meta 设定的 Ray-Ban Stories 整个生命周期销量目标为 478,000 件。文件中的另一项预测也显示了较低的数字，预计销量为 394,000 辆。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——尼克·科斯托夫对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给萨尔瓦多·罗德里格斯（Salvador Rodriguez）（s <a href="mailto:salvador.rodriguez@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">​​alvador.rodriguez@wsj.com</a> ）和乔安娜·斯特恩（Joanna Stern）（ <a href="mailto:joanna.stern@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">joanna.stern@wsj.com）</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 04:02:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/metas-ray-ban-smart-glasses-fail-to-catch-on-31f6ba4e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/metas-ray-ban-smart-glasses-fail-to-catch-on-31f6ba4e<author><![CDATA[Salvador RodriguezJoanna Stern]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>专有的</category><category>计算机/消费电子产品</category><category>个人电子产品</category><category>市场研究/公共关系</category><category>公共关系</category><category>广告/营销/公共关系</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>消费类电子产品</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>社交媒体平台/工具</category><category>技术</category><category>可穿戴技术</category><category>企业战略/规划</category><category>新产品/服务</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>产品与服务</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>个人技术</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>苹果</category><category>AAPL</category><category>元平台</category><category>梅塔</category><category>马克·扎克伯格</category><category>企业战略</category><category>规划</category><category>新产品</category><category>服务</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>产品</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>个人技术</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>电脑</category><category>消费类电子产品</category><category>个人电子产品</category><category>市场调查</category><category>公共关系</category><category>广告</category><category>营销</category><category>商业</category><category>消费服务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>媒体</category><category>娱乐</category><category>社交媒体平台</category><category>工具</category><category>技术</category><category>可穿戴技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Workers to Employers: We’re Just Not That Into You]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在大流行后的经济中，我们生活得更多，工作更少<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001102816"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="531" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827913?width=860&amp;height=531" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">大多数雇主已经不再敦促员工全职返回办公室。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：安德鲁·卡瓦列罗-雷诺兹/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001102816"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/greg-ip"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-733523/AM" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline">叶<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/greg-ip" itemprop="url" rel="author">格雷格</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 2 日晚上 9:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/workers-to-employers-were-just-not-that-into-you-71dbeb6e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>早期，远程工作看起来是双赢的：员工可以随时随地工作，而雇主则可以提高工作效率。</p><p>事实证明，这笔交易只实现了第一部分。员工仍然喜欢远程工作，但最近的研究发现，生产力并没有提高，而且完全远程工作的情况有所下降。</p><p>然而，大多数雇主已经放弃激励员工全职返回办公室。根据人力资源管理协会 (SHRM) 的数据，62% 的雇主至少在一段时间内提供远程工作的选择。人口普查局发现，39% 的员工在家远程办公，其中一半每周工作五天。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>这是自疫情爆发以来人们对工作态度发生更广泛转变的征兆。尽管劳动力市场历来紧张，但<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pay-raises-are-finally-beating-inflation-after-two-years-of-falling-behind-3e89bc2d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">直到最近工资的</a>增长速度还没有快于通货膨胀。原因之一是工人们不仅仅是为了钱讨价还价。他们还要求更多的非金钱补偿，例如带薪休假和灵活的工作时间。因此，他们投入的时间往往较少，或者在投入的时间内完成的工作较少。</p><p>这似乎让员工更加快乐。世界大型企业联合会 (Conference Board) 5 月报告称，2022 年<a href="https://www.conference-board.org/research/job-satisfaction" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">员工满意度较 2021 年大幅上升</a>，达到 1987 年调查开始以来的最高水平。这并不是因为员工发现自己的工作更有成就感，而是因为工作占用的生活时间更少。在调查的18个组成部分中，“工作兴趣”对今年满意度上升的贡献最小；工作与生活的平衡是最大的。 （工资接近中间水平。）</p><p> Memes such as “ <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/labor-market-mystery-where-are-the-older-gen-z-workers-11668278379?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">work your wage</a> ,” “ <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/if-your-gen-z-co-workers-are-quiet-quitting-heres-what-that-means-11660260608?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">quiet quitting</a> ” and “ <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-career-goal-of-the-moment-is-a-lazy-girl-job-f5075c4e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">lazy-girl jobs</a> ” attest to the lesser priority many people today place on career.他们与首席执行官发生了冲突，这位首席执行官通常工作时间不合理，为了公司的利益而牺牲休闲和家庭时间，并认为其他人也应该这样做。 The result: Executives who try to force employees back to the office often <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-new-ceo-says-employees-cant-work-remotely-after-all-and-they-revolt-81135399?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">have a revolt</a> on their hands.</p><p> The conventional wisdom is that happier workers are more productive. That isn&#39;t necessarily because happiness increases productivity, but because an employer, to keep its most productive employees, must keep them happy—even if that means taking steps that make them less productive. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=839822A9-3A5F-4A5D-9390-E94EDF4A2336&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fworkers-to-employers-were-just-not-that-into-you-71dbeb6e&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">人工智能在白领工作中发挥着越来越重要的作用，能够起草电子邮件、演示文稿、图像等。工人已经因技术而失业，一些首席执行官正在改变未来的招聘计划。 《华尔街日报》解释道。插图：雅各布·雷诺兹<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>There is nothing unusual about workers favoring something other than money.加州大学圣地亚哥分校经济学家瓦莱丽·雷米在一封电子邮件中表示：“在上个世纪，平均工作变得更加愉快、不那么繁重。” One reason is government regulations, “but part is…workers&#39; real income has risen over time and they have decided to &#39;spend&#39; (by accepting lower wages) part of that income on better job amenities.”</p><p> In a 2009 study, Ramey and Neville Francis reported that <a href="https://econweb.ucsd.edu/~vramey/research/Century_Published.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">the average number of hours</a> men aged 25 to 54 worked per week fell from 49.8 in 1920 to 41.4 in 1940. That reflected a shift from the six- to five-day week—as famously implemented by Henry Ford and later enshrined in the 1938 Fair Labor Standards Act, which mandated overtime pay for more than 40 hours of work a week.</p><p> Hours continued to decline, though more slowly, until 1980. Separate data suggest they have been largely stable for the past few decades in the US, while trending lower in Europe.</p><p> There are signs that in the wake of the pandemic, Americans, like Europeans, are putting more priority on the “life” part of the work-life balance, and employers are responding. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="532" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827922?width=700&amp;height=532" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Employees relish doing their jobs from home because it saves on commuting and other aggravations.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Andrew Caballero-Reynolds/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> According to SHRM, the share of employers offering paid time off has risen from 63% in 2019 to 70% now, and the share offering paid parental leave has risen from 28% to 39%. Leave averages seven weeks for fathers and nine weeks for mothers, according to human-resources consultants <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WTW" class="">WTW</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span></p><p></p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/american-workers-are-finally-taking-guilt-free-vacations-f5eb383f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Employees are also taking more vacation</a> . Since 2021 some have enjoyed the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-to-sign-bill-making-juneteenth-a-federal-holiday-11623944038?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">first new federal holiday</a> in four decades, Juneteenth.</p><p> The upshot is that even as employment grows rapidly, employees <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/lots-of-hiring-but-not-so-much-working-d4f01646?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">work fewer hours</a> now than in 2019, according to monthly Labor Department data. Its annual American Time Use Survey, meanwhile, found the share of employed people actually working on a given day fell from 67.8% in 2019 to 66.1% in 2022, the lowest since at least 2003. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827999?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Meanwhile, the hours workers do put in are less productive. Output per hour in the business sector shot up early in the pandemic then trended lower through the first quarter of this year, though it likely recovered a bit in the second quarter (the Labor Department reports the latest data on Thursday).</p><p> These are notoriously volatile figures.但其中一些可能反映了我们工作方式的变化。 Employees love working from home because it saves on commuting and other aggravations, and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-workers-really-spend-their-days-d06c8f5f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">lets them pursue personal matters</a> during the day such as going for a run or picking up the kids from daycare.他们可以在晚上或周末补上错过的工作。</p><p> Employees think they&#39;re 7.4% more productive working from home, according to surveys conducted by Nicholas Bloom of Stanford University and two co-authors.他们的经理却持相反的看法，估计员工在家工作的效率会降低 3.5%。 The reason, according to the economists&#39; review of recent research, is that communicating with an employee at home is more cumbersome and time-consuming, while reduced social interaction and feedback diminish creativity and learning.</p><p> Many workers find distractions, from the fridge to the television, at home. The authors note international chess players perform worse remotely, despite the motivation of prize money and rankings, proof that “overcoming potential self-control issues may not be easy.”</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>How has the power dynamic between employee and employer shifted in your workplace?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Employers might be less willing to let employees work from home if the economy eventually slides into a recession and unemployment rises. “We&#39;re probably not in steady state at this point, and some reversal of the movement toward remote work seems likely to me,” said Katharine Abraham, a labor economist at the University of Maryland.</p><p> Bloom is less sure.他和他的合著者得出的结论是，生产力的损失仅限于那些全职远程工作的人，而不仅仅是每周工作几天的人。即使生产力受到影响，成本节约也可能足以弥补。远程员工可能需要更少的办公空间、住在更便宜的地方并接受更低的工资：作者发现，员工认为每周在家工作两到三天相当于加薪 8%。 It will take more than the threat of unemployment to undo this shift in values.</p><p> Write to Greg Ip at <a href="mailto:greg.ip@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">greg.ip@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 01:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/workers-to-employers-were-just-not-that-into-you-71dbeb6e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/workers-to-employers-were-just-not-that-into-you-71dbeb6e<author><![CDATA[Greg Ip]]></author><category> Economic Performance/Indicators</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>工作与生活的平衡</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>远程办公</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Valerie Ramey</category><category> Katharine Abraham</category><category> Nicholas Bloom</category><category> economic performance</category><category> indicators</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>工作与生活的平衡</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>远程办公</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Buying a Home From a Builder? What to Know First]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The do&#39;s and don&#39;ts of purchasing a brand-new home <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827447/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Photo illustration by Rachel Mendelson/The Wall Street Journal, Scott Olson/Getty Images <span>Photo illustration by Rachel Mendelson/The Wall Street Journal, Scott Olson/Getty Images</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001101322"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001101322"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/veronica-dagher" itemprop="url" rel="author">Veronica Dagher</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 2, 2023 9:00 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/buying-newly-built-home-tips-mistakes-437b3cbb"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> For those frustrated with the lack of existing houses on the market, buying from a builder seems like a simple solution—until it isn&#39;t.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-home-sales-boom-builders-6c736630?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Brand-new homes</a> have become more popular in neighborhoods where homeowners are reluctant to put their homes on the market and forgo their <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/low-mortgage-rates-home-sales-low-supply-899aab29?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">low-interest-rate mortgages</a> .</p><p> New-home sales account for around 15% to 20% of all recent home sales and could reach 30% in some markets, compared with a historical average of 10%, said Lawrence Yun, chief economist at the National Association of Realtors.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> The price gap between new homes and old ones has been shrinking and is the smallest in nearly 20 years, said Sheharyar Bokhari, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/RDFN" class="company-name">Redfin</a> senior economist.根据商务部的数据，2023 年 6 月售出的新房销售价格中位数为 415,400 美元。 That compares with $410,200 for existing homes, according to the NAR.</p><p> Builders, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-pandemic-ignited-a-housing-boombut-its-different-from-the-last-one-11615824558?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">fueled by pandemic profits</a> , are also offering incentives to help buyers reduce their <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-dow-jones-07-20-2023/card/mortgage-rates-fall-by-most-since-march-hzzZcqsEcSvYn5evwFCi?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">mortgage rate</a> or closing costs.</p><p> Hayley and Tyler Dupee recently bought a brand new four-bedroom, two-bath home in Ladson, SC, for about $312,000, motivated by the builder-included incentives such as a smart-home security system and window blinds.</p><p> “It became a no-brainer to us that a new home was going to be the best option for us within our budget,” she said. The couple gave up on buying an existing home after seeing bidding wars and the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/home-renovation-delays-plumbers-electricians-a9e3d8e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">pricey renovations</a> needed.</p><p> Buyers might be able to move into an existing home more quickly but could face <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/buying-homes-fixer-uppers-renovations-73e0202f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">expensive repairs and upgrades</a> .新房往往更贵，买家通常需要灵活调整入住日期，因为可能会延迟竣工。建筑商建造的房屋通常带有一些定制选项。 On average, it takes more than eight months to build a house, according to the Commerce Department.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What advice do you have for buying a newly built home?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> With a brand-new home, buyers might misunderstand their purchase contracts, cut corners in the wrong places and balk at delays, financial advisers and builders say.</p><p> Here are five things to consider when purchasing from a builder:</p><h3> 1. Which upgrades are worth it?</h3><p> Consider what upgrades are difficult and pricey to complete once the house is finished, be it a gas line for an outdoor grill or wiring for outlets. These improvements cost less when you are building the home, said Angie Hicks, chief customer officer at home-services company <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/ANGI" class="">Angi</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span></p><p> It is also important to think about your home&#39;s resale value when deciding where to spend or skimp, she said.</p><p> Invest in systems that keep your home running, such as plumbing and electrical, and in areas with a high return on investment, such as the kitchen, she said. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          edgetoedge
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/1e355341-07d6-4ab3-a46c-131c535dad68.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> A simple way to save: Choosing a 36-inch upper kitchen cabinet instead of a 42-inch upper one might cost a buyer about $600 less, depending on size of kitchen, said</p> Donnie Evans, president of Altura Homes, a home builder in Dallas.<p></p><h3> 2. Choose which corners to cut</h3><p> There are some areas where buyers can reduce costs without compromising quality, said Evans.</p><p> Evans has shaved about $1,500 off the price of a roughly 2,000 square-foot home he built for customers by lowering the steepness of the roof from 8/12 pitch to 6/12. Angi 的希克斯表示，屋顶坡度将屋顶陡度表示为垂直高度与水平跨度的比率。 A roof that rises 6 inches in the span of 12 inches would have a 6/12 pitch.</p><p> Selecting square corners for the home&#39;s drywall instead of rounded ones could save about $200 in total for an average 2,000 square-foot house, said Evans. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/ab690f8e-c514-4e25-bbf5-cf14f2835360.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><h3> 3. Read the fine print</h3><p> Home builders typically have some ability to substitute materials based on availability to meet deadlines.</p><p> Read the developer&#39;s contract carefully and note what choices can be overridden by the builder and in what circumstances, said Emily Irwin, senior director of advice at <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WFC" class="">Wells Fargo</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span> Irwin has clients who selected an interior paint color only to find out that the builder is exercising its right to use a different one.</p><p> Top-of-the line stoves and refrigerators, often displayed in model homes, aren&#39;t necessarily included in a standard builder home, said Jason Katz, a financial adviser with UBS Financial Services in New York City. Ask your builder what, if any, appliances are included with your house.</p><h3> 4. Have extra money ready</h3><p> Builders often have the right to increase prices based on material costs, said Charlene Wehring, a financial adviser in Bellville, Texas. If costs go up and buyers can no longer afford the home, they will probably lose their deposit after backing out of the deal, she said.</p><p> Read the contract carefully and factor this possibility into your budget.</p><p> Bokhari at Redfin advises setting aside roughly 10% to 15% for contingency budgeting, depending on the home&#39;s location, type and size. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          edgetoedge
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/7fd8f6f9-675e-48e3-8ba1-38e1040507ec.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><h3> 5. Don&#39;t expect perfection</h3><p> Buyers sometimes think they don&#39;t need a home inspection before closing because their new home usually comes with a warranty, said Mark Barnes, a Realtor in Charleston, SC</p><p> A warranty often covers items such as materials, workmanship, system and structural defects.</p><p> Barnes recommends buyers get a pre-drywall inspection since a home&#39;s problems might not be discovered until after the warranty period ends.</p><p> Hicks at Angi said to get an inspection at three points during the home-building process: before the foundation is poured;在安装干墙之前，更容易解决电气问题； and at the end, to ensure everything is built to code.</p><p> Hicks recommends paying an independent inspector to check out the house.大多数买家花费 280 至 400 美元进行检查。 It is worth it, she said.</p><p> Some of the most common issues that inspectors find are humidity in the home, cracks in drywall or incorrectly installed siding.</p><p> Write to Veronica Dagher at <a href="mailto:Veronica.Dagher@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Veronica.Dagher@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/71bc0361-db4b-4906-bd2f-516bd9b31bf4.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 01:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/buying-newly-built-home-tips-mistakes-437b3cbb</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/buying-newly-built-home-tips-mistakes-437b3cbb<author><![CDATA[Veronica Dagher]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>Building Construction</category><category> Residential Building Construction</category><category>建造</category><category>Real Estate/Construction</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>个人财务</category><category>房地产/物业</category><category>Buying/Selling a Home</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Home Buying &amp; Selling</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>个人财务</category><category>房地产</category><category>财产</category><category>buying</category><category> selling a home</category><category> home buying &amp; selling</category><category> building construction</category><category> residential building construction</category><category>建造</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[SALT Deduction Cap Vexes GOP After Vexing Democrats After Vexing GOP]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Tax bill stalls as Republicans in areas with high levies insist on changes <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105493"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828391?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Jason Smith is under pressure to raise or scrap the limit on the state and local tax deduction.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: J. Scott Applewhite/Associated Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105493"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/richard-rubin" itemprop="url" rel="author">Richard Rubin</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 2, 2023 9:00 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/salt-deduction-cap-vexes-gop-after-vexing-democrats-after-vexing-gop-5da55434"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> WASHINGTON—The $10,000 cap on the state and local tax deduction is bedeviling Congress. Again.</p><p> Taxpayers who itemize deductions can get a federal break for state and local income- and property-tax payments. Republicans in 2017 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/house-gop-moves-toward-keeping-partial-state-and-local-tax-deduction-1507827859?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">limited that deduction</a> to help pay for tax cuts, and the new restrictions largely pinched high-income people in high-tax states.</p><p> That decision split the GOP, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/democrats-salt-tax-cap-high-earners-11635460218?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">divided Democrats</a> who tried to repeal it, and just sparked yet another intraparty fight.</p><p> The latest dispute over what is colloquially known as the SALT cap pits a group of suburban Republicans against the rest of their party. The lawmakers, who largely hail from competitive districts in high-tax states, say they will block a GOP tax bill unless the top tax writer, Rep. Jason Smith (R., Mo.), agrees to raise or scrap the $10,000 limit.</p><p> “In my district, if you own a home and you have a job, you hit the $10,000 cap,” said Rep. Mike Garcia, a Republican who represents a Los Angeles-area district. “This issue and our ability to navigate the SALT is going to be what allows us to keep the majority.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828621?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Rep. Mike Garcia of California says GOP control of the House hinges on the state and local tax deduction cap.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：亚历克斯·布兰登/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>In Congress, geography sometimes trumps ideology, and the SALT cap scrambles the usual partisan discourse regarding taxes. Republicans oppose raising taxes on top earners, but most support the cap because it reduces what they see as a federal subsidy for residents of high-tax states. Democrats who oppose the cap run into objections in their own party because the break mainly benefits high-income people.</p><p> The SALT cap, meanwhile, is most hated in suburban districts in high-tax states that have been among the hardest-fought races in recent elections. Those areas gave Democrats <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ten-takeaways-from-the-2018-midterm-elections-1541580721?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">control of the House</a> during the Trump administration and were pivotal in the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/gop-gains-college-educated-and-minority-voters-in-slim-house-pickup-11668853803?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">shift to a narrow GOP majority</a> last year.</p><p> Now the issue is complicating legislation that Smith and House GOP leaders want to pass that would reverse business-tax increases that Republicans baked into the 2017 law and that took effect in recent years. Without quick action by Congress, many small research-intensive companies face enormous tax bills because of a provision that changed <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/small-businesses-face-big-tax-bills-from-research-deduction-change-a189b113?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">how they deduct research costs</a> . </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1644" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/ed86620f-5ff9-4126-9c33-a13c0cd2b8b6-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> While Smith&#39;s bill doesn&#39;t address the SALT cap, it would temporarily expand the standard deduction for individuals. That would make the $10,000 limit less important for some households.</p><p> Smith, who leads the House Ways and Means Committee, said he has been meeting with Republicans from high-tax states and is confident he has enough votes to get his bill through the House after Congress&#39;s summer break. It appears unlikely to become law as written. Democrats are open to business-tax changes but also want to expand the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hopes-fade-for-year-end-tax-deal-in-congress-to-aid-companies-children-11670769560?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">child tax credit</a> in ways that Republicans oppose.</p><p> Smith suggested that SALT cap changes could be possible in an end-of-year bipartisan bill—but not now.</p><p> “You don&#39;t vote against a bill because of what&#39;s not in it,” Smith said.</p><p> The SALT fight has dogged lawmakers for years. In 2017, House Republicans considered eliminating the deduction before settling on the $10,000 cap. The House passed that bill with 12 Republicans opposed, but Smith and House Speaker Kevin McCarthy (R., Calif.) don&#39;t have that cushion now with their 222-212 majority.</p><p> “I&#39;m going to continue to stand firm,” said Rep. Nick LaLota (R., NY), who represents eastern Long Island and is seeking a much higher cap, at least. “This is oxygen to many of my constituents. This is the one thing that cuts through all the partisan BS.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828397?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Rep. Nick LaLota of New York state favors raising the limit on state and local tax deductions.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：安娜·钱梅梅克/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>Garcia, the Los Angeles-area lawmaker, would prefer no cap but said he would settle for doubling it. Leaving it at $10,000, he said, would be “a continuation of this middle-finger mentality” toward his constituents.</p><p> “I&#39;ve been very blunt with Jason Smith,” Garcia said. “We can have these conversations now when you&#39;re the chairman, or we can have these conversations in two years when you&#39;re the ranking member.”</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> Rep. Andrew Garbarino</p> (R., NY) said lawmakers are getting cost estimates for some options to ease the cap and are looking for ways to offset the fiscal impact.<p></p><p> The 2017 law reduced taxes for most people, even in high-income, high-tax states. But the measure&#39;s changes to rates, brackets and deductions were less visible than the quick comparison of a property-tax bill with the $10,000 threshold.</p><p> Suburban districts helped give Democrats the House majority in the 2018 election—and prompted a new SALT battle. Lawmakers from California, New Jersey and New York insisted on raising or repealing the cap in any tax legislation, using a “No SALT, No Deal” rallying cry. The House eventually passed a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-spending-bill-senate-salt-immigration-11637430938?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">bill with an $80,000 cap</a> , but it flopped in the Senate and never became law.</p><p> Rep. Richard Neal (D., Mass.) was Ways and Means chairman then. He watches Republicans struggle now and describes himself as overjoyed.</p><p> “In the minority, they made it sound simple,” he said. “They&#39;ve now discovered that their majority hinges upon six people who really need some SALT relief.”</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Should the $10,000 cap on state and local tax deductions be repealed?为什么或者为什么不？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> The cap became more onerous over time because it doesn&#39;t increase with inflation. But states have created <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/states-help-business-owners-save-big-on-federal-taxes-with-salt-cap-workarounds-11653989400?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">workarounds for business owners</a> , so the burden now largely falls on wage earners and property owners.</p><p> Neal wants the chairmanship back in 2025, which could shift the problem back onto his shoulders. If Congress does nothing, the cap disappears after that year. State and local taxes would be fully deductible, although expiring changes to the alternative minimum tax would limit the break for many.</p><p> But all of the 2017 tax cuts for individuals also expire after 2025. If lawmakers want to extend them without making deficits even larger than projected, the SALT cap is an obvious tool. The provision raises a lot of money, and it does so from people with very high incomes.</p><p> “What I would hope is that policy makers grapple with trade-offs,” said David Kamin, a former senior aide to President Biden. “If you&#39;re not going to do the SALT limitation, then there should be reduced tax cuts.”</p><p> Write to Richard Rubin at <a href="mailto:richard.rubin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">richard.rubin@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 01:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/salt-deduction-cap-vexes-gop-after-vexing-democrats-after-vexing-gop-5da55434</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/salt-deduction-cap-vexes-gop-after-vexing-democrats-after-vexing-gop-5da55434<author><![CDATA[Richard Rubin]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>政府财政</category><category>政府预算/税收</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政府财政</category><category>政府预算</category><category>税收</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Qualcomm, Stung by Sluggish Smartphone Market, Plans Layoffs]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>公司季度盈利未达预期，前景黯淡<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105820"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="428" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828713?width=700&amp;height=428" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">高通估计，今年的手机销量将至少下降高个位数百分比。</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: ALY SONG/REUTERS </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105820"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/asa-fitch" itemprop="url" rel="author">阿萨·菲奇</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 2 日下午 6:23 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/qualcomm-qcom-q3-earnings-report-2023-2e422521"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/QCOM" class="">高通公司</a><span class="company-name-type">股价</span>周三下跌，此前这家手机芯片制造商公布的销售业绩令人失望，并表示预计将进行新一轮裁员。</p><p>高通公司为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AAPL" class="">苹果</a><span class="company-name-type">iPhone</span>和数百万部Android手机生产芯片，在其核心手机芯片业务下滑的情况下，该公司一直<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/qualcomm-qcom-q2-earnings-report-2023-99c0fd5a?page=1&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在新领域寻求增长</a>。国际数据公司 (International Data Corp.) 的数据显示，智能手机销量在疫情期间激增，但最近几个季度陷入停滞，其中第二季度同比下降 7.8%。</p><p>高通周三表示，最新季度手机芯片营收为 52.6 亿美元，与去年同期相比下降 25%，低于 FactSet 调查中分析师的预期。</p><p>该公司股价周三盘后交易中下跌超过 7.5%。</p><p>高通在周三的一份报告中估计，今年的手机销量将至少下降高个位数百分比，并将其归因于全球经济疲软和中国复苏缓慢。</p><p>在此背景下，高通首席执行官克里斯蒂亚诺·阿蒙在与分析师的电话会议中表示，该公司将进一步削减成本。该公司在一份监管​​文件中表示，这将主要包括裁员，但没有具体说明有多少工作岗位将受到影响。截至去年 9 月，高通拥有约 51,000 名员工，此前曾在经济低迷时期进行过裁员。</p><p>首席财务官 Akash Palkhiwala 表示：“在我们看到基本面持续改善的迹象之前，我们的运营框架不会立即复苏。”他补充说，成本削减措施将持续到公司下一财年。</p><p>总体而言，高通的销售额下降了 23%，至 84.5 亿美元，低于华尔街的预期。其利润下降一半以上，至 18 亿美元。</p><p>高通本季度营收预期中值为 81 亿美元至 89 亿美元，也低于预期。</p><p>高通季度业绩低迷之际，个人电脑市场全面复苏，帮助提升了芯片制造巨头英特尔及其竞争对手超微半导体公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AMD" class="">(Advanced Micro Devices)</a> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/intel-intl-q2-earnings-report-2023-13010e83?page=1&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">第二季度的销售额</a><span class="company-name-type">，</span>该公司最近几天公布了业绩。</p><p>写信给 Asa Fitch： <a href="mailto:asa.fitch@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">asa.fitch@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/d90969df-db3f-4890-9f4e-2892f502493a.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 02 Aug 2023 22:23:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/qualcomm-qcom-q3-earnings-report-2023-2e422521</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/qualcomm-qcom-q3-earnings-report-2023-2e422521<author><![CDATA[Asa Fitch]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>corpearnings</category><category>计算机/消费电子产品</category><category>电信设备</category><category>半导体</category><category>个人电子产品</category><category>手机/移动电话</category><category>计算</category><category>电脑硬件</category><category>消费类电子产品</category><category>移动设备</category><category>工业电子</category><category>工业品</category><category>集成电路</category><category>技术</category><category>企业战略/规划</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>销售数据</category><category>Earnings Projections</category><category> Labor/Personnel</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>裁员/裁员</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>个人技术</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>高通</category><category>高通</category><category>企业战略</category><category>规划</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>销售数据</category><category>earnings projections</category><category> labor</category><category> personnel</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>裁员</category><category>裁员</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>个人技术</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>电脑</category><category>消费类电子产品</category><category>电信设备</category><category>半导体</category><category>个人电子产品</category><category>细胞</category><category>手机</category><category>计算</category><category>电脑硬件</category><category>移动设备</category><category>工业电子</category><category>工业品</category><category>集成电路</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[AMD Keeps the AI Dream Alive Enough]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在今年年底推出主要人工智能芯片之前，华尔街对芯片制造商保持乐观<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001104307"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="538" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828111?width=860&amp;height=538" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> AMD 在上海会议上的专区。该公司正在开发专为人工智能用途而设计的新型 GPU。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Cfoto/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001104307"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dan-gallagher" itemprop="url" rel="author">丹·加拉格尔</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 2 日上午 11:33 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amd-keeps-the-ai-dream-alive-enough-36f95a84"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AMD" class="company-name">Advanced Micro Devices</a>计划以轰动一时的方式结束这一年。投资者迫不及待地庆祝。</p><p>这家芯片制造商通常被称为AMD，是今年仅次于<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NVDA" class="">英伟达的</a>第二热门半导体股票<span class="company-name-type">。</span>这意味着周二晚间发布<a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-08-02-2023/card/amd-falls-after-earnings-sparks-selloff-in-nvidia-and-other-chip-stocks-rlZ68nHQKXSRoFlJ7nNi?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">第二季度业绩</a>之前，该公司股价上涨了 82%，考虑到该公司近期面临的个人电脑市场依然低迷的压力以及传统数据支出的减少，股价上涨了 82%。随着科技巨头<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-alone-cant-save-the-chip-industry-from-a-downturn-81f11199?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">将注意力转向实现生成人工智能所需的工具，这些</a>组件成为核心组件。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828304?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> AMD 的结果确实反映了这一现实。收入同比下滑 18%，至约 54 亿美元，而调整后营业收入则大幅下滑 47%，至约 10.5 亿美元。两者均略高于华尔街的预测，但数据中心部门的收入仍出现自 AMD 2021 年开始公布业绩以来的首次下降，并且低于分析师的预测。一个值得注意的亮点是该公司个人电脑芯片制造部门的收入，尽管比一年前下降了一半以上，但仍比目标高出 23%。</p><p>但 AMD 有一个<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amds-superchips-face-a-trillion-dollar-hurdle-904fa5ad?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">伟大的人工智能故事要讲</a>。这家成功打破英特尔在数据中心中央处理器芯片市场垄断的芯片制造商正在开发一种新型图形处理器（GPU），专为数据中心的人工智能应用而设计。这将使 AMD 与<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/nvidia-can-handle-being-in-the-trillion-dollar-club-1ec9e453?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">人工智能芯片巨头</a>英伟达展开竞争，英伟达的股价今年表现优于 AMD。</p><p>凭借多年开发芯片和开发人员使用的必要软件库，英伟达在人工智能领域建立了非常强大的进入壁垒。但 AMD 显然对自己的产品充满信心，因此设定了一些相当大胆的目标。该公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/federal-reserve-meeting-interest-rate-hike-expected-may-2023/card/amd-bets-on-a-big-second-half-hDCm8bLurBZwtaVM9Uhc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">三个月前表示</a>，预计今年下半年数据中心收入将比上半年增长50%。在周二的财报电话会议上，该公司确认了这一目标，但补充说，大部分收益将在第四季度推出，届时该公司将推出新的 GPU 芯片。分析师目前预计 AMD 第四季度数据中心收入为 22.6 亿美元，比 AMD 2021 年开始公布这些业绩以来该领域的收入高出 37%。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=419229E6-2C0B-46A8-8C1C-60F5B5BFD5BE&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Famd-keeps-the-ai-dream-alive-enough-36f95a84&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">自 20 世纪 80 年代以来，英特尔一直统治着中央处理器市场。但竞争对手AMD去年的市值超过了英特尔，部分原因是在芯片设计上的昂贵押注。 《华尔街日报》的阿萨·菲奇 (Asa Fitch) 解释了各公司为争夺计算机大脑而展开的斗争。<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>华尔街仍然大部分支持； FactSet 的数据显示，近三分之二的分析师将 AMD 视为买入。但这比今年年初的 77% 有所下降，因为一些人出于对高风险产品发布前估值的担忧而下调了该股的评级。一些人正确地指出，<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="">微软</a><span class="company-name-type">、</span>谷歌和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Meta Platforms</a>等正在积极构建 genAI 能力的科技巨头很高兴能有一家替代 Nvidia 的供应商。 AMD 首席执行官苏姿丰 (Lisa Su) 在周二的电话会议中指出，新的数据中心芯片将“增加我们公司的毛利率”，提振了市场情绪。花旗集团分析师 Christopher Danely 将此作为他周三将 AMD 股票评级上调至买入评级的一个因素。</p><p>尽管如此，人们对该公司盈利报告的反应不一，这表明 AMD 在今年剩余时间里可能会出现多么不稳定的情况。财报公布后，该股周二盘后交易中上涨逾 3%，但周三上午又下跌逾 6%，原因是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fitch-downgrades-u-s-credit-rating-56c73b89?mod=hp_lead_pos1&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">美国政府债务评级大幅下调</a>，大盘面临抛售压力。与 Netflix、Spotify 和 Uber 等主要科技公司在本财报季业绩好坏参半后近期出现的下跌相比，这仍然是一个温和的反应。在这个市场上，成为人工智能军火商仍然具有一定的防弹品质。</p><p>写信给 Dan Gallagher： <a href="mailto:dan.gallagher@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dan.gallagher@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 02 Aug 2023 15:33:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/amd-keeps-the-ai-dream-alive-enough-36f95a84</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/amd-keeps-the-ai-dream-alive-enough-36f95a84<author><![CDATA[Dan Gallagher]]></author><category>计算机/消费电子产品</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>半导体</category><category>计算</category><category>电脑硬件</category><category>工业电子</category><category>工业品</category><category>集成电路</category><category>技术</category><category>图形处理单元</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>内容类型</category><category>列</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Advanced Micro Devices公司</category><category>AMD</category><category>英伟达</category><category>NVDA</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>内容类型</category><category>列</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>电脑</category><category>消费类电子产品</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>半导体</category><category>计算</category><category>电脑硬件</category><category>工业电子</category><category>工业品</category><category>集成电路</category><category>技术</category><category>图形处理单元</category></item></channel></rss>